"1520","1540":"1540","about 1568":"circa 1568","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England","1666951, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edworth, Bedford, England":"Edworth, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dymock, Gloucestershire,England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1540–1569":"1540–1569","1535–1569":"1535–1569","1559–1644":"1559–1644","1566–1644":"1566–1644","1568–Male":"1568–Deceased","1520–1540":"1520–1540","1524–1540":"1524–1540","Aft 1540":"after 1540","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1568":"1568","1535":"1535","3 March 1559":"3 March 1559","1644":"1644","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","about 1568":"about 1568","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England","1666951, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Edworth, Bedford, England":"Edworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Dymock, Gloucestershire,England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gamon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Alfredo, Jesus, Luis, Alejandro, Angel, Arsenio, Ernesto, Esperanza, Gregoria, Javier, Jose Angel.","Spanish (<b>Gamón</b>): probably a topographic name from <i>gamón</i> ‘asphodel’.","English: variant of   Gammon   or   Game  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gammon","meanings":["English:","nickname from a diminutive (‘little leg’) of <i>gamb</i>, the Norman form of <i>jambe</i> ‘leg’; <i>mb</i> would be assimilated to <i>mm</i>, hence <i>Gammon</i>. Compare French <i>Gambet</i>, <i>Gambin</i>, <i>Gambon</i>.","variant of   Game  ."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":29,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Gamon was born in 1540, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, her father, John Gamon, was 21 and her mother, Mary Holmes, was 17. She married Edmund Hankyns in 1565, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1569, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1540–1569":"1540–1569","1535–1569":"1535–1569","1559–1644":"1559–1644","1566–1644":"1566–1644","1568–Male":"1568–Surnud","1520–1540":"1520–1540","1524–1540":"1524–1540","Aft 1540":"pärast 1540","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1568":"1568","1535":"1535","3 March 1559":"3. märts 1559","1644":"1644","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","about 1568":"umbes 1568","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Hinxworth, Hertfordshire, England","16669